        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Revd S Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>Kind Friend and Zealous Israelite.<lb/>  Fearing you may think your good advice &#38;<lb/> generous offer&#44; in regard&#44; to instruction&#44; in our<lb/> holy tongue&#44; falls &#40;in my case&#41; upon needless<lb/> ears&#59; I take this means of informing you<lb/> how sincerely I regret&#44; that Irving&#44; will not<lb/> this year be able to avail himself of the<lb/> opportunity&#44; so nobly&#44; and so kindly furnished<lb/> but his lessons&#44; at the High School&#44; make<lb/> such heavy demands&#44; upon his time&#44; that<lb/> he is obliged to study and write&#44; each and<lb/> every day far into the evening hours&#44; having<lb/> <sic>realy</sic> not a moments time&#44; for exercise or<lb/> recreation&#44; which I greatly deplore&#44; fearing<lb/> the tax&#44; both on brain&#44; &#38; eyesight.  Estille<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>and Clarence make good progress under<lb/> the kind care of Miss <sic>Piexotto</sic> at the<lb/> house once a week&#44; but Irving has no<lb/> time even to embrace this opportunity.<lb/>  Trusting you will feel&#44; how much I request<lb/> existing circumstances&#44; &#38; hoping for better<lb/> in the near future<lb/></p>
            <p>I am as ever<lb/>
                With much esteem<lb/>
                Myrtilla E Mitchell<lb/>
                2120 Vine st.<lb/>
                Phila. Nov 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1878<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Enclosed please find synopsis of the sermon of<lb/> Henry Mendez&#44; cut from the New York Herald<lb/> of to day.<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
